text:
This section assesses whether a PEM electrolyser stack can be connected directly to a wind turbine’s internal DC link without an additional DC/DC converter between the turbine DC link and the PEM stack.
The target architecture is:
wind generator -&gt; active front-end rectifier / turbine-side converter -&gt; controlled DC link -&gt; PEM stack or PEM stack array
The assumed system has:

no AC grid export;
no grid-side inverter;
no electrolyser-side DC/DC converter;
no dedicated stack current regulator;
only protection or auxiliary devices such as DC-link capacitance, contactors, precharge circuits, dump load, brake chopper, crowbar, and emergency shutdown hardware.

The turbine-side rectifier is assumed to be an active front end (AFE). It controls generator torque and DC-link voltage. The PEM stack or PEM stack array is connected directly to this controlled DC bus.

What the active front end must do
In this architecture, the active front end is not just a rectifier. It becomes the main electrical control device for the whole hydrogen-production system.
It must:

regulate DC-link voltage;
control generator torque;
limit stack current by limiting DC-link voltage;
curtail wind power when the PEM stack cannot accept more current;
coordinate with pitch control, brake control, and dump-load protection;
handle fast stack trips without DC-link overvoltage;
support controlled start-up, shutdown, and restart;
avoid low-current or unsafe gas-crossover operating regions;
coordinate with PEM water, pressure, gas-purity, and thermal limits.

This is the core engineering trade-off: removing the DC/DC converter is possible, but its control and protection functions must move into the turbine converter, stack segmentation, and balance-of-plant controls.

Most credible no-DC/DC architecture
The most credible no-DC/DC architecture is:
PMSG wind turbine -&gt; active front-end rectifier -&gt; controlled DC link -&gt; segmented PEM stack array
with:

the AFE regulating DC-link voltage;
generator torque control providing MPPT or curtailed operation;
PEM modules switched in and out to keep current density in range;
optional series/parallel stack reconfiguration;
DC-link capacitor for short transients;
brake chopper or dump load for stack rejection and emergency events;
balance-of-plant interlocks for water, temperature, pressure, and gas purity.

This architecture is more credible than a purely passive rectifier because the AFE gives active voltage and torque control. It is also more credible than one large directly connected stack because modular stack switching gives a coarse but effective way to adapt the load to wind availability.

What replaces the missing DC/DC converter
Removing the electrolyser-side DC/DC converter does not remove the need for control. It relocates the control function.
In a conventional system, the DC/DC converter or rectifier supply normally provides:

stack current control;
voltage matching;
current limiting;
current ripple reduction;
controlled start-up and shutdown;
some degree of electrical decoupling;
fault management and protection.

In the direct DC architecture, these functions must be provided by the integrated system:

the AFE regulates DC-link voltage;
generator torque control limits the mechanical-to-electrical power conversion;
pitch control curtails aerodynamic power when required;
stack modules can be switched in and out to adjust the effective PEM load;
optional series/parallel reconfiguration can adjust stack voltage range;
a DC-link capacitor handles short electrical transients;
a brake chopper or dump load handles stack rejection and emergency overvoltage;
balance-of-plant interlocks ensure water, temperature, pressure, and gas-purity limits are respected.

The most credible architecture is therefore:
PMSG wind turbine -&gt; AFE -&gt; controlled DC link -&gt; segmented PEM stack array
with module switching and emergency dump/brake protection.

Implication for the model
For modelling purposes, direct DC integration can be represented as an architecture that removes the grid-side inverter and the electrolyser-side rectifier/DC conversion stage from the hydrogen-production power path.
The assumption is justified because:

the PEM stack is a DC load;
the turbine already has a controlled DC link;
industrial concepts explicitly propose direct connection of the electrolyser to the turbine DC link;
academic work supports direct DC bus connection with modular PEM stack arrays;
small-scale experiments have shown direct wind-to-PEM coupling without voltage converters;
the missing DC/DC functions can be replaced by AFE control, stack segmentation, and protection systems.

The model should nevertheless treat this as an integrated turbine-electrolyser configuration, not as a conventional turbine plus conventional electrolyser package. The feasibility depends on co-design.
